Adaptive Predictive Photonic RealSense Processing Node

Description

The device is extended into an adaptive modular photonic processing node for real-time 3D interaction. Instead of sending the full RealSense stream directly into a conventional computer for all processing, the RealSense camera provides raw RGB, depth, infrared, point-cloud, confidence, and timing data to a modular processing system.

This system splits the incoming sensor stream into several specialized channels: depth, point cloud, motion/change, silhouette/body structure, feedback/memory, effect modulation, and final fusion/output. Each channel can be processed by a dedicated photonic or hybrid photonic-electronic module.

The key idea is that the device does not only extract parameters from the scene. It also receives feedback from its own processing modules, predicts the next state of the scene, and reconfigures the modules before the next frame or control cycle. This allows the system to react not only to what the RealSense currently sees, but also to where the person, body volume, motion, and projected image are expected to be moments later.

Abstract

This concept describes an adaptive photonic-AI processing node for RealSense-based real-time 3D interaction. The system uses a RealSense depth camera as a fast spatial sensor, but moves heavy processing away from the laptop or conventional rendering computer. The incoming RGB, depth, infrared, and point-cloud streams are distributed into multiple specialized processing modules.

The proposed modules include a Depth Module, Point Cloud Module, Motion and Prediction Module, Silhouette/Body Module, Feedback/Memory Module, Effect Modulation Module, and Fusion/Output Module. Each module processes a specific channel of the sensor data and produces a corrected, predicted, simplified, or effect-ready output layer.

A central Adaptive Predictive Controller receives scene features and feedback from the modules. It does not merely fade values or switch modules on and off. Instead, it changes internal processing parameters such as sensitivity, region of interest, delay amount, feedback gain, routing, weighting, thresholds, and prediction horizon. In a future photonic implementation, these parameters may correspond to optical phase shifts, attenuation, routing paths, delay lines, resonator states, or programmable photonic weights.

The system therefore forms a closed loop:

RealSense captures the scene.
The input module splits and synchronizes the data.
Specialized photonic-AI modules process depth, motion, point-cloud, silhouette, and feedback channels.
The controller predicts the next scene state and reconfigures the modules.
The fusion module combines the processed layers into a projection-ready output, corrected point cloud, effect map, or metadata stream.

This architecture is designed for real-time interaction between a physical person and their projected or rendered representation on a wall, screen, or spatial installation. The conventional computer can be reduced to a control interface, light compositing layer, or preview system, while the modular photonic node handles the time-critical perception, prediction, feedback, and effect modulation.

System Structure

RealSense Camera
→ Input / Sync Module
→ Depth Module
→ Point Cloud Module
→ Motion / Prediction Module
→ Silhouette / Body Module
→ Feedback / Memory Module
→ Effect Modulation Module
→ Fusion / Output Module
→ Projector / Screen / Laptop Preview

Module Roles

Input / Sync Module

Receives RealSense RGB, depth, infrared, point cloud, confidence, and timestamp streams. It synchronizes the streams and routes them into separate processing channels.

Depth Module

Processes distance information, depth zones, near/far separation, and depth-reactive weighting. It can create cleaned depth maps or depth response maps for interaction.

Point Cloud Module

Receives point-cloud or compressed 3D feature data. It can simplify, stabilize, downsample, predict, or reshape the 3D representation of a person or object.

Motion / Prediction Module

Compares the current state with previous states and estimates motion direction, velocity, change intensity, and predicted future position. This module helps compensate for latency.

Silhouette / Body Module

Builds a body mask, outline, contour, or body-zone representation from depth, motion, and RGB features. It helps the projected image attach to the real body.

Feedback / Memory Module

Stores short-term state through delay, decay, echo, accumulation, or optical feedback. This module can create physical temporal behavior such as trails, inertia, resonance, or delayed response.

Effect Modulation Module

Combines depth, motion, silhouette, and feedback data into effect-control maps. These maps can drive distortion, glow, displacement, projection deformation, intensity, or interaction strength.

Fusion / Output Module

Combines the outputs of all modules into a final projection-ready image, corrected point cloud, effect layer, metadata stream, or lightweight output for a conventional computer.

Adaptive Predictive Controller

The controller is the central logic layer of the system. It receives both RealSense features and module feedback. Based on this information, it predicts the next state of the interaction and reconfigures the modules.

It can change:

* depth sensitivity;
* motion threshold;
* prediction horizon;
* point-cloud density;
* region of interest;
* silhouette sharpness;
* feedback gain;
* delay path;
* effect intensity;
* routing between modules;
* fusion weights.

In a photonic implementation, these control values may correspond to optical phase, attenuation, delay, routing, resonance, wavelength selection, or programmable photonic weights.

Core Idea

The device is not only a sensor and not only a renderer. It is an adaptive photonic-AI processing node that receives 3D scene data, predicts the next state of the interaction, reconfigures its internal modules, and outputs already processed visual or spatial layers.

The goal is to reduce the conventional computer’s role from full real-time processing to control, preview, and light compositing. The time-critical logic is moved into specialized modules that can eventually be implemented as photonic neural processing blocks.

Final Concept

The system can be described as a modular photonic-AI co-processor for RealSense-based real-time 3D interaction. It receives raw sensor streams, splits them into specialized channels, processes them through adaptive modules, predicts future scene states, and outputs corrected, predicted, and effect-ready visual layers with minimal latency.
